\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\fs28\kerning0\highlight8\insrsid3440241 \tab \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 A DaemonSet in Kubernetes ensures that a copy of a Pod runs on every node (or a subset of nodes) in the cluster.
\par \tab \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 When a new node is added ? the pod is automatically deployed on \tab it.
\par \tab \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 When a node is removed ? the pod is automatically deleted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\fs28\cf1\lang9\langfe16393\kerning0\langnp9\insrsid3440241 \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 Why Use a DaemonSet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\fs28\cf1\kerning0\insrsid3440241 \tab \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 DaemonSets are ideal when you need per-node tasks or m\hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 onitoring agents, such as:
\par \tab \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 Monitoring agents: Prometheus Node Exporter
\par \tab \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 Log collection agents: fluentd
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1  Simple DaemonSet YAML
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 apiVersion: apps/v1
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 kind: DaemonSet
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 metadata:
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1   name: node-exporter
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1   namespace: default
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 spec:
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1   selector:
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1     matchLabels:
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1       app: node-exporter
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1   template:
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1     metadata:
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1       labels:
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1         app: node-exporter
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1     spec:
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1       containers:
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1       - name: node-exporter
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1         image: prom/node-exporter:latest
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1         ports:
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1         - containerPort: 9100
\par ---------------------------------------------
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1  What is Helm?
\par \tab \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 Helm is a package manager for Kubernetes, similar to how:
\par \tab \tab \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 apt is for Ubuntu/Debian,
\par \tab \tab \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 yum is for CentOS/RedHat.
\par \tab \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 It helps you define, install, and manage Kubernetes applications easily using pre-configured templates called Charts.
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af31505\loch\f1 Chart = A package of pre-configured Kubernetes resources (YAML \tab \tab     templates + default configs).
\par ---------------------------------------------
